    "caption": "The sky's sharpest eyes, riding thermals with barely a wingbeat.",
    "shortDescription": "Eagles can spot a rabbit from three kilometres up in the air — their eyes have two focal points instead of one, giving them roughly eight times sharper vision than a human. They soar on rising columns of warm air called thermals, barely moving their wings, saving energy for the sudden dive. Fun fact: Eagle eyes are so large they take up most of the skull and cannot move in their sockets, so eagles must turn their whole head to look around."
